🚀 Most APIs don’t fail because of bad logic… they fail because of poor performance decisions.

You can have the best architecture on paper—but if your APIs are slow, everything else suffers.
The truth?
 API performance isn’t about one silver bullet. It’s about layering the right optimizations.
Here are 5 techniques that consistently make a real difference 👇
🔹 Pagination
 Stop returning everything at once.
 Break large datasets into smaller, manageable chunks to reduce response time and improve user experience.
🔹 Asynchronous Logging
 Logging shouldn’t slow down your API.
 Push logs to buffers and process them asynchronously to keep requests fast and non-blocking.
🔹 Caching (e.g., Redis)
 Why hit the database repeatedly for the same data?
 Cache frequently accessed responses and dramatically reduce latency.
🔹 Payload Compression
 Large payloads = slow APIs.
 Use GZIP/ZIP to compress responses and speed up data transfer across the network.
🔹 Connection Pooling
 Opening DB connections repeatedly is expensive.
 Reuse them efficiently to improve throughput and reduce overhead.
💡 Real impact when done right:
✔ Lower latency
 ✔ Higher throughput
 ✔ Better scalability under load
 ✔ Improved user experience
🔁 Key takeaway:
 High-performing systems aren’t built on one optimization—
 they’re built on a stack of smart, intentional decisions.
💬 Which of these have you implemented—and what impact did you see?
 Anything you’d add to this list?
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
TRACE : Returns the full HTTP request received by the server for debugging and diagnostic purposes.
OPTIONS: Return the HTTP Methods supported by the server for the request URL.
CONNECT: Converts the request connection to a transparent TCP/IP tunnel for secure communication.
PURGE: Invalidates a cached resource.
LOCK: Locks the resource for exclusive use by the client.
UNLOCK: Unlock the resource previously locked by the client.
MKCOL: Creates a new collection resource.
COPY: Copies the resource identified by the Request-URI to the destination URI.

--------------------------------------------------------------
HTTP Status Codes:
    1XX: Informational
    2XX: Success
    3XX: Redirection
    4XX: Client Errors
    5XX: Server Errors
    